ond in innumerable well-rehearsed ways. Diasporas construct racialized, sexualized, gendered, and oppositional subjectivities and shape the cosmopolitan intellectual commitment of scholars. The diasporic individual often has a double consciousness, a privileged knowledge and perspective that is consonant with postmodernity and globalization.The essays in this volume reflect on the movements of people and cultures in the present day, when physical, social, and mental borders and boundaries are being challenged and sometimes successfully dismantled. The contributors - from a variety of disciplinary perspectives - discuss the diasporic experiences of ethnic and racial groups living in Canada from their perspective, including the experiences of South Asians, Iranians, West Indians, Chinese, and Eritreans. Diaspora, Memory, and Identity is an exciting and innovative collection of essays that examines the nuanced development of theories of Diaspora, subjectivity, double-consciousness, gender and class experiences, and the nature of home.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAutobiographical memoryzCanada. 0aGroup identityzCanada. 0aHomexPsychological aspects. 0aHomexSocial aspectszCanada. 0aIdentity (Psychology)zCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aAgnew, Vijay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAgnew, Vijay, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBabbitt, Susan E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDunlop, Rishma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHua, Anh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJames, Carl E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKadar, Marlene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabu